Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. This was found out by scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on the question of why children resist tickling so fiercely, only to demand more.
After all, it has also been shown why just approaching a tickling hand triggers laughter before touching. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebrum, which already triggers laughter at the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, previous research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans. This "laughter" is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touch
So far, it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - so therefore people can not tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers have now found in the experiments on the rats that laughter as well as the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during self-contact. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. During the foreign touch and tickling by the scientists, however, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh were intensified.
But if the self-touch and the touch by others happen at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the rat brain cannot distinguish between self-touch and touch by others. The new findings suggest that people cannot tickle themselves because self-touch activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. In the experiment, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely, showing flight behavior or paralysis. This ambivalence is similar to the behaviour of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral response that is the same in rats and humans.
