The Iranian Revolutionary Guards detained the tanker on July 19 on charges of disregarding maritime law regulations in the Persian Gulf. Seven of the 23 crew members had already been released at the beginning of September. The remaining 16 crew members are doing well under the circumstances, Hånell said. They had behaved professionally in view of the difficult and stressful situation in the past ten weeks. The shipping company is now working on reuniting them with their families as soon as possible.
The British government suspected behind the arrest of the "Stena Impero" a reaction to a similar incident in the British Gibraltar: At the beginning of July, a supertanker with oil from Iran, which was said to have been destined for Syria, was chained there. According to the authorities, the delivery violated EU sanctions against war-torn Syria. The British had received the reference to the ship from the USA.
Iran spoke of "piracy" and threatened consequences. In mid-August, the "Adrian Darya-1" was finally released. London vehemently rejected speculations that it had been a barter deal to free the "Stena Impero".
