TÜV inspections in the terminal: BER boss: No more "showstoppers" for capital airport
For two months, it was examined whether the complicated system network in BER fire protection works together. The operators are satisfied with the course of events. But the TÜV is not yet finished at BER.
After large-scale TÜV inspections in the terminal of the future capital airport, the operators confirmed the planned opening in October next year. This is certain, said Supervisory Board Chairman Rainer Bretschneider after a meeting of the Supervisory Board.
Airport boss Engelbert Lütke Daldrup spoke of a successfully completed audit, but also said that there were still deficiencies in the terminal to work through. "We have a lot of detailed topics, but we don't have a real showstopper." He assured that the timetable until commissioning still contained buffers.
However, there are indications that the time reserve should not be too large. The construction completion notice is now to be submitted to the building authority in the course of the first quarter of 2020, at the beginning of the year this was planned for this autumn.
Hundreds of power cable deficiencies remain to be repaired; the TÜV wants to test these until February. "In order to create the conditions for the start of flight operations, intensive work must continue to be done on the processing of the deficiencies," it said in a written message.
Lütke Daldrup said that in many cases it is about missing evidence, less about new cables. There is also still no release for all dowels on which the cable trays hang. The airport boss expects this to be available by the end of the year.
In addition, the fire protection at the transition to the station below the terminal is not yet working satisfactorily. The problems had already led the project into another crisis three years ago. This time it's about smoke aprons that come down like a canvas in the event of a fire so that the smoke does not spread. They go down too far. 36 engines therefore have to be replaced. Then there will be new experiments with hot gas smoke at the beginning of the year.
Problems with fire protection and other construction defects as well as planning errors have been delaying the opening of the airport for years. It was originally scheduled to go into operation in 2011. Since construction began in 2006, costs have risen from two billion euros to an estimated 6.5 billion euros when it opens next year.
Because passenger numbers in Berlin have risen significantly since then, those responsible are planning to expand the airport. This is to be discussed at a special meeting of the Supervisory Board on 18 October, as Chairman Bretschneider announced.
The airport company is now looking for two new managing directors. Chief Financial Officer Heike Fölster will move to Deutsche Bahn at the end of the year, while personnel manager Manfred Bobke-von Camen will retire next year, Bretschneider said. He thanked Fölster. She had put the airport finances on a firm footing.
Chemnitz: Vending machines for drugs blown up - police arrest man
He needed money for drugs - and blew up several vending machines in the Chemnitz city area! Now the perpetrator is finally in custody!
In the past two years, the number of cigarette and parking ticket machines blown up in Chemnitz and the region has risen sharply. There was a loss in the millions!
