AUA takes over Eurowings flights from Vienna
The Lufthansa Group is turning its strategy for Vienna Airport upside down. In the midst of the price war with low-cost airlines such as Lauda, Wizz Air, EasyJet and Level, the Lufthansa subsidiary AUA is taking over "the commercial control of all Eurowings flights from Vienna," a spokesman for Austrian Airlines confirmed to APA on Friday. Previously, "AviationNetOnline" had reported about it.
The Vienna base of Lufthansa's low-cost airline Eurowings will thus de facto be dissolved. Of the current seven Eurowings aircraft, four will remain in Vienna. From January 2020, AUA will take over this in a "wet lease", i.e. including Eurowings personnel. In the future, three Eurowings jets will be stationed in Salzburg, which will fly from Salzburg and Innsbruck as charter aircraft to holiday destinations. Routes from Vienna to Germany will be taken over by Eurowings Germany.
The Eurowings base in Vienna will be integrated into the AUA hub and network planning, the spokesman said. The flight times are to be coordinated with connecting flights. On the one hand, the aim is to strengthen the Vienna hub and, on the other hand, to expand decentralised transport out of the federal states.
