The bill still requires the approval of the Senate. In the three-day emotional debate, critics in the right-wing camp had warned that in the future many "children could grow up without a father". The French Bishops' Conference is also against the innovation.
The new regulation is the core component of a bioethics law, which Health Minister Agnès Buzyn defended as an "opportunity" for society. It depicts the modern family, in which there are children with only one parent or with homosexual parents. According to her, the costs of artificial insemination for all women should be covered by social security.
Fertilization with sperm from dead husband still prohibited
By a narrow majority, however, the National Assembly rejected an amendment that would give widows access to the sperm of their dead husband for artificial insemination. In Belgium, Spain and Great Britain, artificial insemination is permitted "post-mortem". In Germany, there have been cases in the past in which women sued in vain for the surrender of the sperm of a deceased person. The opponents of the initiative in Paris argued that such a child would then bear a "particularly difficult fate".
Numerous deputies of the governing party La République en Marche (The Republic on the Move, LREM) of President Emmanuel Macron and members of the opposition had spoken out in favour of artificial insemination with the sperm of the deceased partner. They emphasized that a widow would be subjected to a "double mourning" if the death of her husband also left her desire to have children unfulfilled.
The initiators of the now failed amendment consider it unfair that a widow can be fertilized in the future with the sperm of an unknown person, but not with that of her own partner.
So far, artificial insemination in France is only allowed to heterosexual couples who cannot father children. You must be married or live together for at least two years. Buzyn had already announced in the summer that surrogacy would remain prohibited.
In Germany, artificial insemination is theoretically open to all women - but it is often difficult for single people or lesbian couples.
