Half of Europe's tree species are threatened with extinction
In addition to pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are also causes of the threat, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) reported on Friday in Brussels. She examined the populations of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of them do not occur on any other continent. Of these 265, 58 percent are threatened. 66 are already at the highest level of endangerment and thus on the verge of extinction.
The IUCN divides endangered species into six categories: from "potentially endangered" to "endangered", "critically endangered", "critically endangered" and "extinct in the wild" to "extinct". In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide as endangered.
Mountain ash and wild horse chestnut threatened
In Germany, especially mountain ash (Sorbus) are threatened, said one of the authors, David Allen, the German press Agency. "Most are threatened because populations are small anyway or by the conversion or weakening of their habitats."
It also looks bad for the wild common horse chestnuts. They have been considered "vulnerable" since 2017, level two of the IUCN scale. In addition to a fungus, the biggest threat is the Balkan leaf miner moth. It has been spreading from southeastern Europe across the continent since the 1980s and has hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnuts (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe at less than 10,000 individuals. Trees in cities, parks and avenues are not taken into account in this assessment.
Shrub species and mosses also in danger
At the same time, IUCN scientists established new European Red Lists for molluscs, shrubs and mosses. More than a fifth of molluscs and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened, according to the IUCN. This is mainly due to the destruction of wilderness, introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Molluscs such as snails play a key role in recycling nutrients in the soil and are an important food source for birds and other animals.
"This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of the European ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet," said Luc Bas, IUCN Director of the Europa Office. "We need to limit the impact of humans on our ecosystems and make the protection of these species a priority."
Earthquake off Istanbul: 34 injured reported
34 people were injured in the recent earthquake in Turkey. There were no deaths, according to the information. Dozens of people had to leave their homes, 14 schools in Istanbul had been closed for security reasons, said Turkish Vice President Fuat Oktay on Friday.
