Cook bankruptcy: Hotels get money from the insurance
According to a press report, the bankruptcy of the travel provider Thomas Cook is likely to cost some banks dearly. There is a threat of high write-downs on outstanding bonds and loans. This also affects Credit Suisse, writes the "Financial Times" in its edition on Friday.
Banks such as Barclays, Morgan Stanley, UniCredit or Credit Suisse would probably have to make write-downs of up to 1.8 billion British pounds (around 2 billion euros) on their books, according to the report. This was shown by estimates by the consulting firm AlixPartners.
Bondholders would have to accept write-downs of £900 million to £1 billion and lenders between £550 million and £825 million. The actual amounts to be written off are likely to be at the upper end of the ranges, an expert told the paper.
