If the provider promises too much performance
If the Internet connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options.
Anyone who concludes an Internet contract does not need to blindly trust the speed specifications of the providers. In the event of abnormalities, customers can check for themselves how much of this is actually achieved.
After all, the previously promised transmission rates are part of the contract and should therefore also be achieved, explains the consumer center Bavaria.
If the connection always seems much slower than advertised by the provider, there are various test options. For example, the measurement tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transmission rates and compare them with the rate agreed in the contract.
"However, the tests of the providers are carried out according to provider-specific specifications and are therefore not uniformly and objectively calculated," says the Bavarian Consumer Center on its side.
If the connection is much slower than announced, customers can set the provider a reasonable deadline of usually 14 days to provide the promised service. This is best done by those affected in writing by registered mail.
If this does not work even after repeated requests, customers can terminate the contract and, under certain circumstances, also claim damages. But in the absence of success, only the legal action helps.
First Senior Republican for Investigation
As the first high-ranking Republican, the governor of Vermont has spoken out in favor of an impeachment investigation against US President Donald Trump. "I think the investigation is important, yes, and where that leads from here is determined by the facts that are established," Phil Scott said at a press conference Thursday. He wanted to know more about the whistleblower affair before measures - impeachment proceedings can lead to the removal of the president - are taken.
