Aegean Sea: Baby and four other children drown in boat accident
When a refugee boat capsized in the Aegean Sea, a baby and four other children drowned. A total of seven people died in the accident, as the Greek coast guard announced on Friday. The nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were rescued.
Currently, hundreds of migrants are crossing from Turkey to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean. Last year, 174 people were killed on this route, according to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). Federal Interior Minister Horst Seehofer has now announced his intention to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU Commissioner, he wanted to find out in Turkey "how the refugee situation stands," Seehofer said on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the "administrative problems of the Greeks" in Athens in order to be able to help them cope.
A spokeswoman for the EU Commission confirmed on Friday Seehofer's planned trip with EU Home Affairs Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and French Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
Greece continues to receive an unusually high number of migrants from Turkey. On Tuesday alone, 654 people crossed over to the Greek islands, the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection said on Wednesday.
Does the Turkey deal still work?
The increased numbers recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This allows the EU to send back all refugees and migrants who enter the Greek islands illegally via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in one Syrian refugee from Turkey for every Syrian deported.
However, the processing of asylum applications is making slow progress on the Greek side due to a lack of staff. According to the Ministry of Civil Protection, almost 29,400 people are holding out on Lesbos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos. The situation is worst on Lesvos: 5200 migrants are currently accommodated in a camp with capacity for 650 people.
Never since the entry into force of the EU-Turkey refugee pact in March 2016 have there been so many, reported the state radio.
Climate change: Heat leads to more heart attacks
According to doctors, climate change will put the health system to the test in the future. Climate change is "certainly" one of the biggest challenges for the health system in the next 20 to 50 years, said Andreas Zeiher, President of the German Society of Cardiology. Especially the cardiovascular system was affected by high temperatures and large temperature jumps within a short time and led to increased heart attacks. Especially people with cardiovascular diseases, the elderly and diabetics are affected.
Green politician has to answer for embarrassing photo glitch
The leader of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign - was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green leader holds a reusable cup in her hand in a photo. But now it came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa/Canada - It went unnoticed for quite a long time - and finally attracted attention. Elizabeth May, the leader of the Canadian Greens, has never held the reusable coffee mug with a metal straw in her hand. On the party's website, she was seen in a photo with this cup, talking to citizens. However, the photo had already been published before and also distributed to the media - and then the cup was still a disdainful (cardboard) cup, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Green leader has to answer for photo glitch
The National Post then accused May of manipulation and that the party produced fake news in order to appear more credible on the subject of "environmental protection". And this in the middle of an election campaign for the lower house election, in which Trudeau is also having an increasingly difficult time because of a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media, fueling discussion about fake news. One user shares a comparison of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their leader to hide their disposable cup".
May was shocked and asserted on her blog that she knew nothing about this action. To underline this, she immediately posted the original: She, talking to citizens, a cup in her hand. However, she corrected, it was made of bamboo. She always has him with her. A spokeswoman for the party said it was only about putting the party logo in the picture, not to cover up anything. Only a section of the photo can be seen on the website.
May writes that she feels sorry for the employee who did so. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide," she told the Guardian and at the same time asked her over-committed team: "If they feel like editing a picture again, couldn't they do something with my face so that I look younger?"
The German Greens have also gotten into shitstorms because of their use of disposable plastic or because of air travel - but their pictures were not photoshopped. The leader of the Bavarian Greens, Katharina Schulze, ate ice cream with a plastic spoon on holiday, as merkur.de* reported.
Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifetime flight ban at Cathay
Allegedly, Jaqueline Ng had been assured by mail from Cathay Pacific an upgrade. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously getting an upgrade for Business Class - that's what many passengers dream of. Sometimes they're lucky, and check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class for free.
However, this case shows how not to do it: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. Jaqueline Ng has more than 65,000 followers on Instagram. She flew from Taiwan to New York on May 30 and back on June 7.
On the outbound flight, the employees refused to upgrade Jaqueline, although she had shown an email in which Cathay Pacific allegedly promised her an upgrade. The influencer claims to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline. The airline, on the other hand, accuses Jaqueline of having forged the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK Airport were skeptical: they followed up with headquarters. And indeed, the employee from whom the mail allegedly originates is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
The airline employees at the airport cancelled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifetime flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (about 1,280 euros) she had to buy a new flight ticket to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Cathay had refunded her the price of her original ticket, but Jaqueline also claimed back the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. The airline's terms and conditions also state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with this - and now calls in a lawyer.
Oil prices fall after report of ceasefire in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar within a very short time on Friday afternoon. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - around 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of American West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The trigger for the price slide was a report in the Wall Street Journal about a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia in mid-September brought five percent of global oil production to a standstill. The Iranian-allied Houthi rebels in the civil war country Yemen had claimed the attacks for themselves. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse political tension in the region.
If an agreement is reached, it could focus on growth and demand concerns, Ole Hansen, head of commodity strategy at Saxo Bank, told Bloomberg.
Oil prices are thus continuing their downward movement of recent days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost almost 59 dollars, Brent almost 65 dollars.
Most recently, Bloomberg reported, citing insiders, that repair work on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than expected after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original amount.
Recently, there have been several press reports, citing insiders who report rapid progress by the state oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there were signs of some easing in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: The British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leaving the port more than two months after it was seized by Iran and recently cleared. The crew is now preparing the departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping company boss Erik Hånell told Swedish radio in a text message on Friday morning.
However, the US announced that it would deploy defensive missiles and soldiers to the Iranian archenemy in Saudi Arabia. The fear of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the USA and Great Britain had driven up oil prices significantly at times in recent weeks.
